    {
      "question": "Given the equations $\\frac{7}{x+y} + \\frac{1}{x-y} = 3$ and $\\frac{21}{x+y} - \\frac{2}{x-y} = 1$, the value of $\\frac{1}{x+y}$ is:",
      "answer": "(C)",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Let $p = \\frac{1}{x+y}$ and $q = \\frac{1}{x-y}$.",
          "The equations become $7p + q = 3$ and $21p - 2q = 1$.",
          "Multiply the first equation by $2$ to eliminate $q$: $14p + 2q = 6$.",
          "Add this to the second equation: $(14p + 2q) + (21p - 2q) = 6 + 1$.",
          "This simplifies to $35p = 7$.",
          "Solving for $p$, we get $p = \\frac{7}{35} = \\frac{1}{5}$."
        ],
        "derivation": "$7p + q = 3 \\\\ 21p - 2q = 1 \\\\ 14p + 2q = 6 \\\\ 35p = 7 \\\\ p = \\frac{1}{5}$"
      },
